{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641658"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17894"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.46,0,0.04,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114654"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96657"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24723"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114654"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances is released by the liver during ketogenesis and used by tissues for energy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acetone","Acetoacetyl CoA","Hydroxy-B-methylglutaryl CoA","Succinate","Beta-hydroxybutyrate"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring ketogenesis, the liver produces ketone bodies, primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-hydroxybutyrate\u003C/strong\u003E and acetoacetate, which are released into the bloodstream. These ketone bodies are then taken up by peripheral tissues, such as muscle and brain, where they are oxidised to provide energy, especially during periods of fasting or low carbohydrate intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetone\u003C/strong\u003E is a byproduct of ketone body metabolism and is not used as a primary energy source. It is often excreted in the breath and urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetoacetyl CoA\u003C/strong\u003E is an intermediate in the synthesis of ketone bodies but is not released into the circulation for energy use by other tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxy-B-methylglutaryl CoA\u003C/strong\u003E is an intermediate in the synthesis of ketone bodies and cholesterol but is not released into the circulation for energy use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuccinate\u003C/strong\u003E is an intermediate in the citric acid cycle and is not directly involved in ketone body metabolism or released by the liver during ketogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During ketogenesis, the liver produces ketone bodies, including acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate, which are released into the circulation.","Beta-hydroxybutyrate is a major ketone body used by peripheral tissues for energy during periods of fasting or low carbohydrate intake.","Acetone is a byproduct of ketone body metabolism but is not a primary energy source."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 72; pg. 887.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020;64(4):607-47.","Wang Y, Wu R. The effect of fasting on human metabolism and psychological health. Dis Markers. 2022;2022:5653739.","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, glucose metabolism. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024.","Chandel NS. Lipid metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021;13(9):a040576."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96657"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17894"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96657"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:43:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:43:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10608"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114654"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/